\begin_layout Quote
More generally, a series of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $‚àëùëê_{n}(ùë•‚àíùëé)^{n}=c_{0}+ùëê_{1}(ùë•‚àíùëé)+ùëê_{2}(ùë•‚àíùëé)^{2}‚Ä¶$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
power series in 
\begin_inset Formula $(x-a)$
\end_inset


\series default
 or a 
\series bold
power series centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\series default
 or a 
\series bold
power series about 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Theorem 3.15: 
\series default
For a given power series 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum c_{n}\left(x-a\right)^{n}$
\end_inset

 there are only three possibilities: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
i.
 The series converges only at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
ii.
 The series converges for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
iii.
 The series converges if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x-a\right|<R$
\end_inset

 and diverges if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x-a\right|>R$
\end_inset

, where the positive number 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

