 was formulated by the Scottish mathematician James Gregory and formally
 introduced by the English mathematician Brook Taylor in 1715.
 Who was Brook Taylor? He was the one invented Integration by part: ‚à´ ùë¢ùëëùë£
 = ùë¢ùë£ ‚àí ‚à´ ùë£ùëëùë¢ If the 
\series bold
Taylor series is centered at zero
\series default
, then that series is also called a 
\series bold
Maclaurin series
\series default
, named after the Scottish mathematician Colin Maclaurin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Theorem 3.17: 
\series default
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a power series representation at 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, that is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}c_{n}\left(x-a\right)^{n}$
\end_inset

